sols_latex:
Because the function $\sin x$ is continuous on the interval $[0,b]$ and
is differentiable on the interval $(0,b)$, we can apply the Mean Value
Theorem. Thus we know that there is some $c$ in the interval $(0,b)$ so
that:

\begin{align*}
\cos(c) &= \frac{\sin(b) - \sin(0)}{b-0} \\
&= \frac{\sin(b)}{b}
\end{align*}

sols_raw:
Because the function &lt;math>\sin x&lt;/math> is continuous on the interval &lt;math>[0,b]&lt;/math> and is differentiable on the interval &lt;math>(0,b)&lt;/math>, we can apply the Mean Value Theorem.  Thus we know that there is some &lt;math>c&lt;/math> in the interval &lt;math>(0,b)&lt;/math> so that:

: &lt;math>\begin{align}
\cos(c) &amp;= \frac{\sin(b) - \sin(0)}{b-0} \\
&amp; = \frac{\sin(b)}{b}
\end{align}&lt;/math>
